		<title>By: Krof Drakula</title>
		<link>http://markos.gaivo.net/blog/?p=266&#038;cpage=1#comment-140871</link>
		<dc:creator>Krof Drakula</dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 24 Jun 2008 08:01:15 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://markos.gaivo.net/blog/?p=266#comment-140871</guid>
		<description>On Windows, you can even have isolated Firefox Portable instances with separate configurations. There&#039;s, I think, an extension that then enables you to sync configuration between multiple instances.

While you can&#039;t run FF2 and FF3 simultaneously (Portable version nags about the running instance of FF3 before starting), you can run them separately, at least. Much less fuss than running a VM for the sole sake of testing on IE6.

Problem is that with the new version, the plugin code needed to be ported, something that doesn&#039;t happen often for some of the less popular extensions. It&#039;s a two-edged sword - the same thing you&#039;re dealing with MS needs to deal with too for their IE8 &lt;meta&gt; tags. Sadly, there&#039;s no good single answer to any of these issues, and almost all of the solutions require a tradeoff the end user has to pay.</description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>On Windows, you can even have isolated Firefox Portable instances with separate configurations. There&#8217;s, I think, an extension that then enables you to sync configuration between multiple instances.</p>
<p>While you can&#8217;t run FF2 and FF3 simultaneously (Portable version nags about the running instance of FF3 before starting), you can run them separately, at least. Much less fuss than running a VM for the sole sake of testing on IE6.</p>
<p>Problem is that with the new version, the plugin code needed to be ported, something that doesn&#8217;t happen often for some of the less popular extensions. It&#8217;s a two-edged sword &#8211; the same thing you&#8217;re dealing with MS needs to deal with too for their IE8 &lt;meta&gt; tags. Sadly, there&#8217;s no good single answer to any of these issues, and almost all of the solutions require a tradeoff the end user has to pay.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
